1650:Treatment analyses were dominated by '"\\"'`treatment_regorafenib'"\\"'`. In an adjusted main-effect model without interactions, regorafenib was associated with +0.943 months of PFS (p<1e-300). Follow-up interaction models showed that this average association was highly heterogeneous. In a joint model, the regorafenib association was reduced by '"\\"'`kras_mutation'"\\"'` (-1.763 months interaction), '"\\"'`right_sided_primary'"\\"'` (-1.475 months), '"\\"'`braf_v600e'"\\"'` (-1.760 months), and increasing '"\\"'`cea_ng_ml'"\\"'` (-0.0249 months per ng/mL); all were overwhelmingly significant. The initially suggested '"\\"'`nras_mutation'"\\"'` interaction did not remain significant after accounting for those modifiers (+0.0749 months, p=0.11). A refined subgroup analysis confirmed concentration of the regorafenib signal: among patients with '"\\"'`kras_mutation=0'"\\"'`, '"\\"'`right_sided_primary=0'"\\"'`, '"\\"'`braf_v600e=0'"\\"'`, and '"\\"'`cea_ng_ml<50'"\\"'`, regorafenib-treated patients had mean PFS of 6.945 months versus 4.117 months without regorafenib, a +2.828 month difference (p<1e-300). In the complementary adverse composite group, the unadjusted regorafenib difference was only +0.032 months and was not significant (p=0.257).
